              "kp_id": "KP01",
              "claim_supported": "biological problem and signal-response framework"
            }
          ],
          "text_runs": [
            {
              "text": "Signal control is a conversion problem in which a defined cue must be detected, converted into intracellular change and translated into altered physiology. ",
              "source_type": "lecture_slide_core",
              "source_anchor": "fixture_lecture_slides.pdf slides 10-11",
              "highlight": "none",
              "in_text_citation": null
            },
            {
              "text": "Signal duration can alter downstream-state stability by prolonging pathway occupancy under sustained stimulation, so timing as well as amplitude affects the final response. ",
              "source_type": "extra_reading_book",
              "source_anchor": "fixture_extra_reading.pdf chapter 2 section signal duration",
              "highlight": "yellow",
              "in_text_citation": null
            },
            {
              "text": "Control is therefore best explained as a sequence from detection to mechanism to consequence.",
              "source_type": "lecture_slide_core",
              "source_anchor": "fixture_lecture_slides.pdf slide 11",
              "highlight": "none",
              "in_text_citation": null
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "paragraph_id": "H2",
          "function": "heading",
          "is_heading": true,
          "lecture_anchors": [],
          "text_runs": [
            {
              "text": "2 Mechanism and evidence",
              "source_type": "student_visible_transition",
              "source_anchor": null,
              "highlight": "none",
              "in_text_citation": null
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "paragraph_id": "P2",
          "function": "mechanism",
          "lecture_anchors": [
            {
              "file": "fixture_lecture_slides.pdf",
              "slide_or_page_range": "slides 12-14",
              "lecture_id": "L1",
              "kp_id": "KP01",
              "claim_supported": "mechanism, evidence and consequence"
            }
          ],
          "text_runs": [
            {
              "text": "Mechanistically, the signal acts through a receptor-level decision step ",
              "source_type": "lecture_slide_core",
              "source_anchor": "fixture_lecture_slides.pdf slides 12-13",
              "highlight": "none",
              "in_text_citation": null
            },
            {
              "text": "at a receptor phosphorylation site (Author et al., 2026)",
              "source_type": "citation_original_source",
              "source_anchor": "Author et al. 2026 original paper, read section receptor activation",
              "highlight": "green",
              "in_text_citation": "(Author et al., 2026)",
              "citation_original_read": true,
              "micro_detail_insert": true,
              "original_phrase": "receptor-level decision step",
              "inserted_phrase": "at a receptor phosphorylation site",
              "parent_ppt_or_source_slot": "lecture receptor-level decision step controlling downstream pathway activation",
              "question_function": "mechanism",
              "claim_delta": "precision_only",
              "qa_status": "micro_detail_verified"
            },
            {
              "text": " that constrains which downstream pathway becomes active. This explains why the same tissue can remain stable under weak stimulation but shift state when the signal crosses a threshold. ",
              "source_type": "lecture_slide_core",
              "source_anchor": "fixture_lecture_slides.pdf slides 12-13",
              "highlight": "none",
              "in_text_citation": null
            },
            {
              "text": "A blocking experiment showed that receptor inhibition prevented the downstream transition, supporting causal interpretation of the signal-to-response link (Author et al., 2026). ",
              "source_type": "citation_original_source",
              "source_anchor": "Author et al. 2026 original paper, read section Results",
              "highlight": "green",
              "in_text_citation": "(Author et al., 2026)",
              "citation_original_read": true
            },
            {
              "text": "The consequence is that the physiological response can be explained as regulated conversion of signal information into a coordinated output. The answer therefore stays focused on the causal chain from signal detection to pathway selection and functional interpretation, including the threshold logic that makes weak and strong stimulation produce different outcomes.",
              "source_type": "lecture_slide_core",
              "source_anchor": "fixture_lecture_slides.pdf slide 14",
              "highlight": "none",
              "in_text_citation": null
            }
          ]
        }
